    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/lipid-species-annotation-assessment/000",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The score indicating the quality of the match between a library candidate and a target feature is composed of two parts: one measuring the similarity in m/z between the target and candidate and one gauging the similarity of the fragmentation patterns: S = Smz + Sma... For each target feature, a list of the candidates ranked by score is produced, which includes the metabolite name, m/z matched, m/z error (ppm), the number of matched fragments, and score.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly describes ranking candidates by score and producing ranked lists for inspection; chain-level variants (e.g., different PC species) are discussed in context of lipid library structure.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-1c03032",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "lipid-species-annotation-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Inspect, rank, and compare alternative candidate lipid annotations for a given LC-MS feature, evaluating score distributions and chain-level variants to understand annotation confidence and structural ambiguity.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:44:26.975370+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/lipid-species-annotation-assessment/001",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "For each target feature, a list of the candidates ranked by score is produced, which includes the metabolite name, m/z matched, m/z error (ppm), the number of matched fragments, and score. Additionally, a list containing all rank 1 annotations is produced for quick result inspection.",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes ranked candidate lists and multiple annotation outputs; the concept of evaluating lower-scoring alternatives is implicit in the ranking and scoring system design.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-1c03032",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "lipid-species-annotation-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "research_question",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "This skill is essential when a feature matches multiple lipid species or fragments and you need to systematically document which candidates rank highest and why lower-scoring alternatives remain plausible.",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:44:26.975370+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/lipid-species-annotation-assessment/002",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "If RAMClustR is used, the target feature m/z and RT values will be used to locate the corresponding pseudo-MS/MS spectrum (cluster). Alternatively, a RAMClustR R object containing deconvolved pseudo-MS/MS spectra for the features can also be used as data input... The outputs when using RAMClustR deconvolved pseudo-MS/MS are equivalent except that EICs for the matched features are not shown",
      "asbval:note": "Paper describes use of RAMClustR objects (RC objects) as input to MetaboAnnotatoR; annotateRC is the function name in the card, which aligns with RAMClustR-based annotation workflow.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-1c03032",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "lipid-species-annotation-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "Apply this skill after running MetaboAnnotatoR's annotateRC function when you need to verify that the top-ranked annotation for a feature is correct",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:44:26.975370+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/lipid-species-annotation-assessment/003",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The lipid library covers diverse lipid classes including fatty acids, acylcarnitines, phosphatidic acids (PAs), phosphatidylcholines (PCs), phosphatidylethanolamines (PEs), phosphatidylserines (PSs), phosphatidylglycerols (PGs), sphingomyelins (SMs), lysophospholipids (LysoPA, LysoPC, LysoPE, LysoPS, and LysoPI), ceramides, glucosylceramides, and mono-, di-, and triacylglycerol lipids (MG, DG, and TG, respectively).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly lists PC and LPC (lysophospholipid) classes in the lipid library; the concept of multiple structural variants matching the same feature is central to the annotation workflow.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-1c03032",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "lipid-species-annotation-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "understand what alternative lipid structures (e.g., fragments of related PC species or different LPC regioisomers) could explain the same m/z and retention time",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/ECO_0000033"
      },
      "prov:wasAttributedTo": "anthropic/claude-haiku-4-5-20251001",
      "prov:wasGeneratedAtTime": "2026-06-15T12:44:26.975370+00:00",
      "sepio:credibility_status": {
        "@id": "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/SEPIO_0000338"
      }
    },
    {
      "@id": "asbval:assertion/skill/lipid-species-annotation-assessment/004",
      "@type": "asbval:ClaimAssessment",
      "asbval:evidence_quote": "The outputs allow the analyst to evaluate the quality of the annotation and decide on its confidence... Table with ranked candidates for the target feature (Figure 2C), which provides information on the type of feature (parent or fragment), adduct, and isotope. Additionally, the m/z error between the feature and candidate is shown, as well as the number fragments of each candidate that have been matched to pseudo-MS/MS (fraction).",
      "asbval:note": "Paper explicitly states that ranked outputs allow analysts to evaluate annotation quality and confidence; the ranking system enables comparison of score gaps between candidates.",
      "asbval:perspicacite_kb": "asb-paper-10-1021-acs-analchem-1c03032",
      "asbval:supported_raw": "yes",
      "asbval:target_artifact_id": "lipid-species-annotation-assessment",
      "asbval:target_artifact_kind": "skill_bundle",
      "asbval:target_claim_field": "scope",
      "asbval:target_claim_text": "assess the confidence gap between rank 1 and rank 2+ candidates to decide whether a single annotation is warranted or multiple hypotheses should be retained",
      "eco:evidence_type": {
